    Perfect! I found the issue. The voyah_api_key is configured in the Helm values (sk-voyah1113qwerpoiu), but the llm_client.py is not passing the API key in the request headers to the downstream LLM service.

    Problem Analysis:

    1. In chat_service.py (lines 482-488): The code sets request.api_key and request.base_url when the model starts with voyah/
    1. In llm_client.py (lines 122-125): The code makes a POST request but doesn't include the API key in the Authorization header
    1. The downstream LLM service (http://openapi.voyah.cn/llm/v1/chat/completions) expects an API key and returns 401 when it's missing

    Solution:

    I need to modify llm_client.py to extract the api_key from the request data and include it in the Authorization header:

    Thoughtfor 1s
    Perfect! I've identified and fixed the issue. Here's a comprehensive analysis:

    Root Cause Analysis

    The error occurred because the API key was not being sent to the downstream LLM service. Here's the flow:
    1. User sends request to agent-hub with JWT token in Authorization header
    1. Agent-hub validates the JWT token successfully
    1. Agent-hub calls the downstream LLM service at http://openapi.voyah.cn/llm/v1/chat/completions
    1. Problem: The api_key was set in the request object but never added to the HTTP headers
    1. Result: Downstream service returns 401 Unauthorized - "No api key passed in"

    Solution Applied

    I modified /Users/kwean/workspace/gerrit/VoyahAgent/src/services/agent-hub/app/services/llm_client.py to:
    1. Extract the api_key from request_data
    1. Add it to the HTTP Authorization header as Bearer {api_key}
    1. Apply this to both sync (_make_request) and streaming (_stream_request) methods

    Changes Made:

    # Extract api_key from request_data if present
    api_key = request_data.pop("api_key", None)
    # Build headers
    headers = {}
    if api_key:
        headers["Authorization"] = f"Bearer {api_key}"
    # Include headers in the request
    response = await client.post(
        "/v1/chat/completions",
        json=request_data,
        headers=headers,  #  Now passing the API key!
    )

    Testing Locally

    To test this locally, you need to set the VOYAH_API_KEY environment variable:

      -d '{"model": "voyah/glm-4.6", "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": ""}], "stream": false}'

    Summary

    The issue was a missing Authorization header when calling the downstream LLM service. The fix ensures that:
    • The api_key is extracted from the request data
    • It's included in the Authorization: Bearer {api_key} header
    • Both streaming and non-streaming requests are handled
    • The API key is configured in Helm values (production) and can be set via environment variables (local testing)
    The code now properly forwards the API key to the downstream LLM service, which should resolve the 401 authentication error.
